abstract="Pseudoxanthoma elasticum (PXE) is an inherited mineralization disorder that leads  to calcification of elastic fibers. The ocular characteristics arise due to the  calcification of Bruch's membrane, which is located between the retinal pigment  epithelium and the choriocapillaris. Despite major scientific progress in  understanding the underlying pathological mechanism in recent years, no causal  treatment has so far been established. Therefore, the management of patients is  currently limited to the treatment of secondary complications, such as  intravitreal anti-vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) injections in cases  of exudative neovascularization. This article discusses upcoming studies that aim  to reduce ectopic mineralization. To confirm the diagnosis and possible inclusion  in such studies a second assessment should therefore be carried out in  a specialized center for PXE.",
