pages="1819--1830",
keywords="Aged; Aged, 80 and over; Analysis of Variance; Dark Adaptation/*physiology; Female; Humans; Macular Degeneration/physiopathology; Male; Mesopic Vision/*physiology; Middle Aged; Retinal Drusen/*physiopathology; Tomography, Optical Coherence/methods; Visual Field Tests/*methods; Visual Fields/*physiology",
abstract="PURPOSE: To examine the feasibility and utility of dark-adapted two-color  fundus-controlled perimetry (FCP) in patients with cuticular, reticular, and soft  drusen, and to compare FCP data to microstructural spectral-domain optical  coherence tomography (SD-OCT) data. METHODS: Forty-four eyes (24 eyes of 24  patients with drusen, age 69.4{\thinspace}{\textpm}{\thinspace}12.6 years; 20 normal eyes of 16 subjects,  61.7{\thinspace}{\textpm}{\thinspace}12.4 years) underwent duplicate mesopic, dark-adapted cyan and  dark-adapted red FCP within 14{\textdegree} of the central retina (total of 12{\thinspace}936 threshold  tests) using the Scotopic Macular Integrity Assessment (S-MAIA, CenterVue,  Padova, Italy) device. FCP data were registered to SD-OCT data to obtain outer  nuclear layer, inner and outer photoreceptor segment, and retinal pigment  epithelium drusen complex (RPEDC) thickness data spatially corresponding to the  stimulus location and area (0.43{\textdegree}). Structure-function correlations were assessed  using mixed-effects models. RESULTS: Mean deviation values for eyes with  cuticular, soft, and reticular drusen were similar for mesopic (-2.1, -3.4, and  -3.6{\thinspace}dB) and dark-adapted red (-1.4, -2.6, and -3.3{\thinspace}dB) FCP. For the dark-adapted  cyan FCP (0.1, -1.9, and -5.0{\thinspace}dB) and for the cyan-red sensitivity difference  (+1.0, +0.5, and -2.4{\thinspace}dB), the mean deviation values differed significantly in  dependence of the predominant drusen type (one-way ANOVA; p{\thinspace}<{\thinspace}0.05). RPEDC  thickness was associated with reduction of mesopic sensitivity (-0.34{\thinspace}dB/10{\thinspace}{\textmu}m  RPEDC thickening; p{\thinspace}<{\thinspace}0.001), dark-adapted cyan sensitivity (-0.11{\thinspace}dB/10{\thinspace}{\textmu}m RPEDC  thickening; p{\thinspace}={\thinspace}0.003), and dark-adapted red sensitivity (-0.26{\thinspace}dB/10{\thinspace}{\textmu}m RPEDC  thickening; p{\thinspace}<{\thinspace}0.001). CONCLUSIONS: In contrast to mesopic FCP, dark-adapted  two-color FCP allowed for meaningful differential testing of rod and cone  function in patients with drusen indicating predominant cone dysfunction in eyes  with cuticular drusen and predominant rod dysfunction in eyes with reticular  drusen. RPEDC thickness was the strongest predictor of the evaluated SD-OCT  biomarkers for point-wise sensitivity.",
doi="10.1038/s41433-018-0183-3",
url="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41433-018-0183-3",
url="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30068928",
