keywords="Diabetic Retinopathy/diagnostic imaging/*pathology; Female; Fluorescein Angiography; Fovea Centralis/*blood supply; Healthy Volunteers; Humans; Male; Middle Aged; Retinal Vessels/diagnostic imaging/*pathology; Retrospective Studies; *Tomography, Optical Coherence; Diabetic retinopathy; Foveal avascular zone; Optical coherence tomography angiography",
abstract="PURPOSE: To analyze foveal avascular zone (FAZ) dimensions and symmetry in  patients with diabetic retinopathy (DR) compared to healthy controls using  optical coherence tomography angiography (OCT angiography). METHODS: OCT  angiography was performed via an Avanti® RTVue 100 XR OCT system (Optovue, Inc.,  Fremont, CA, USA) in patients with diabetes mellitus (DM) and healthy adults. A  frame centered on the fovea was used for FAZ measurements. The borders of the  superficial vascular layer were defined as 3 $\mu$m below the internal limiting  membrane (ILM) and 15 $\mu$m below the inner plexiform layer (IPL), and for the deep  vascular layer as15 $\mu$m and 70 $\mu$m below the IPL, respectively. Angles of maximum  FAZ diameter were measured in all eyes by two graders. RESULTS: In healthy eyes  (N{\thinspace}={\thinspace}25), the FAZ surrounding vascular arcades were intact, showing a vertical or  horizontal oval symmetrical formation with a maximum diameter usually on the  horizontal or vertical axis. Diabetic eyes (N{\thinspace}={\thinspace}29) presented with disintegrity  of the vascular arcades, resulting in an enlarged FAZ. In the superficial layer,  the mean horizontal FAZ diameter was significantly larger in the DR group (753 $\mu$m  {\textpm}272 $\mu$m) than in the control group (573 $\mu$m {\textpm}177 $\mu$m, p{\thinspace}={\thinspace}0.029). The difference  was even more pronounced in the deep layer, with a mean value of 659 $\mu$m {\textpm}194 $\mu$m  in the control group and 1009 $\mu$m {\textpm}342 $\mu$m in the DR group (p{\thinspace}={\thinspace}0.001).  Furthermore, in the superficial layer, the angle of the maximum FAZ diameter was  0{\textdegree} ({\textpm}15{\textdegree}) or 90{\textdegree} ({\textpm}15{\textdegree}) in 72.0 {\%} of healthy eyes. In eyes with DR, the angle was  0{\textdegree} ({\textpm}15{\textdegree}) or 90{\textdegree} ({\textpm}15{\textdegree}) in only 6.9 {\%} of cases, due to the irregular  configuration of the FAZ. CONCLUSIONS: OCT angiography is capable of imaging  retinal vasculature without dye injection. Our data suggest that it can detect  disintegrity of the vascular arcades surrounding the FAZ, thus differentiating DM  from healthy eyes. Vascular abnormalities were more pronounced in the deep  vascular layer.",
doi="10.1007/s00417-015-3148-2",
url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00417-015-3148-2",
url="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26338819",
url="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4884570",
language="eng"
}

